<hl>
<seg id=1> U.S. Hopes Asian Countries Will Leave the Mad Cow Fears Behind </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Agence France-Presse, Manila, 14th) - Despite one mad cow case was reported in U.S. last month, U.S. Agriculture Department officials said Asian countries can feel relieved and continue to consume U.S. beef after a short period of time. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> U.S. has immediately stepped up safety testing after the discovery of first mad cow case.  Despite such efforts, several Asian countries, including Japan and South Korea etc., had immediately banned or limited the import of U.S. beef. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> U.S. officials said yesterday the relevant authorities have enlarged the investigations of the mad cow disease.  The beef produced in the area where the mad cow disease was found, had never been exported.  In addition, the relevant authorities have been very stringent in testing and quarantine work in the past 10 years to prevent the spread of mad cow disease. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The mad cow disease is also called bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) and has been linked to the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease in humans, which causes vacuolation and spongiform changes in the human brain. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> "We are very optimistic that these Asian countries will narrow the scope of bans in next month or so," Graham, director of Asian Affairs, U.S. Agriculture Department said. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> "We have guaranteed to all Asian countries that our beef are safe for consumption," Graham said. </seg>
<seg id=8> He said a Japanese delegation is currently in U.S. to study the measures adopted by U.S. to prevent the spread of mad cow disease. </seg>
</p>
