<p>
<seg id=4> The act is the latest of a series of measures to restrict immigration since the Danish Liberal Party leader Rasmussen became Prime Minister in November 2001. </seg>
<seg id=5> Reports say the act is most likely to be endorsed by the parliament as the Liberal Party has won the support from the right-wing Danish People's Party on the immigration issue. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The act requires that children born of foreigners in Denmark apply for citizenship as required for other immigrants when coming of age, instead of being automatically permitted citizenship. </seg>
<seg id=7> Citizenship of immigrants will be deprived of if they commit serious criminal crimes against society. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Over the past two years, the Danish government has brought about a series of restrict measures against immigrants in granting long-term residence permits to them and restricting their family members to enter Denmark. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Due to Danish government's unfriendly policy towards immigrants, the number of foreigners taking refugees in Denmark has fallen from 14,347 in 1993 to 3,500 in 2003. </seg>
<seg id=10> This has damaged Denmark's long-standing image as a free country that cherishes human rights. </seg>
</p>
