<hl>
<seg id=1> Kiharu Nakamura,The Great Japanese Geisha of No Equal of Her Time, Died in New York at The Age of 90 </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP in Tokyo on 7th) The Japanese publisher Soshisha announces that Kiharu Nakamura, who gave up her career as a Japanese geisha and has lived in America for nearly half a century died in her house in New York at the age of 90 on 5th. </seg>
<seg id=3> Soshisha has published 10 books about Kiharu Nakamura including "The Memoir of a Tokyo-born Geisha" a best seller published in 1983. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> "The Memoir of a Tokyo-born Geisha" has been translated into 8 languages and adapted into a TV play and a stage play. The book depicted that Kiharu Nakamura was the only geisha who spoke English in the days before World War II. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> French avant-garde artist Jean Cocteau, king of comedy Charlie Chaplin and US baseball star Babe Ruth were among foreign celebrities who were entertained by Nakamura when they visited Tokyo. </seg>
<seg id=6> Soshisha said that Nakamura gave Jean Cocteau inspiration to write the poem "Geisha". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Soshisha made an announcement that Kiharu Nakamura was born in a doctor's family in a luxurious district of Tokyo. She became a geisha of the New Bridge Entertainment Area at the age of 16 despite the opposition of her parents. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> After years of work as a geisha at New Bridge, Nakamura married a diplomat and soon afterwards they were divorced. </seg>
<seg id=9> After the war, Nakamura returned to her geisha career. She immigrated into the USA in 1956. </seg>
<seg id=10> In US, while teaching traditional Japanese music and dance, Nakamura also served as a consultant for operas, including Madame Butterfly. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Nakamura has a son who is now a university professor of modern arts. </seg>
</p>
