</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Although the number of HIV victims is estimated to be 2.5 million in the country, AIDS and HIV are still taboo subjects in Kenya. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> D'Agostino is in charge of the Nyumbani Orphanage which houses many HIV children. He claims that many of his children are barred from primary schools. The practice of these schools is against the government policy of compulsory primary school education. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Lawyer Nanwamba of D'Agostino said at the court presided over by Judge Koome: "Barring children, especially HIV sufferers, from public schools is inhumane and illegal and violates human rights. Receiving education is a basic human right and turning down these children is an infringement upon their rights." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> D'Agostino is seeking a court order to force the school accept children without inquiring whether or not they are infected with HIV. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The Kenya Ministry of Education said through its lawyer Gacirih that it does not know about the discrimination but understands the practice of the school. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Gacirih said that the Education Ministry is ready to solve the problem through negotiation with Nyumbani Home for Children located on the Northwest Outskirts of Nairobi. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Koome orders the two sides to talk it over and report the result of the talk tomorrow. </seg>
