<hl>
<seg id=1> Political Strife in Iran Is Getting Increasingly Fierce And The Reformists Threaten to Resign </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP in Tehran on 13th) Struggle has erupted between Iranian reformists and powerful conservatives over the candidate qualification for election. Today things are getting worse and several cabinet leaders threaten to resign unless conservatives make concessions on keeping reformist candidates from participating in election. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> One of the Vice-Presidents Sattarifar warns that the whole government may resign if the attempt of the Guardian Council to disqualify thousands of candidates for the parliament election on February 20 is not prevented. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Sattarifar said: "If the government cannot fulfil its duty of protecting people's rights and holding free election, it will not be the option to continue the administration." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Governors of 27 provinces in Iran also threaten to resign together. Persons near President Khatami reveal that at least 10 ministers have prepared their resignations. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> However, some media indicates that President Khatami with a gentle disposition also asks to resign. This is denied by Khatami's assistant. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The angry reformist parliament members are holding their sit-in protest in the parliament building for the 3rd day and say they are ready to continue the sit-in demonstration for weeks. </seg>
<seg id=8> 83 of the reformist parliament members are disqualified so that they cannot participate in election for a second term. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Iranian News Agency (IRNA) says the parliament members have challenged the Guardian Council and demands it to withdraw its decision of disqualifications. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Guardian Council made up of 12 members is not elected by people and is a stronghold for anti-reform right wing forces. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Nobel peace laureate Ms. Ebadi who has been hated by hard liners says she will visit the parliament to show her support to the sit-in demonstration of the reformist parliament members. </seg>
</p>
