<hl>
<seg id=1> The Appreciation of New Zealand Dollar Does Not Affect The Confidence of Entrepreneurs in New Zealand </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP in Wellington on 15th) According to the latest quarterly survey released by New Zealand Institute of Economic Research, people in the business world still have confidence in New Zealand despite the soaring New Zealand dollar. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The report points out that enterprises pessimistic about the enterprise environment in the next 6 months account for only 2%. By contrast the figures in the last 2 seasons were 3% and 20% respectively. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The above-mentioned Institute points out that the indexes in the report show a steady economic growth in the 4th season of last year. The activities of the enterprise field have increased by 31%. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> However, according to the foreseeable goals the economic growth of New Zealand is predicted "to further slide down gradually in the following seasons." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Gardiner, economist with New Zealand Institute of Economic Research, says that New Zealand dollar has been appreciated fast in the past 3 months, which results in widening of confidence difference between exporters and non-exporters. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Predicably, 11% of manufacturing and building exporters will have less promising prospects in the next 6 months and 40% of non-exporters feel optimistic about the enterprises' prospects in the next 6 months. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The New Zealand dollar has appreciated 30 percent over the past two years. </seg>
</p>
