</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> It is not until this week that Weber plays down the delay of Adecco in publishing its annual statements. The statements should have been made public on February 4, but the publishing was delay because major weaknesses of internal control in the business of its North America Manpower Company were found. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Weber's post will be replaced by Chief Accountant Cano for the time being. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Chief executive officer Arrieta of Adecco has also resigned and he will be succeeded by Marcel, Chairman of Adecco France, largest one-country company of Adecco Group in the overseas. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Besides, the former Chairman Bowmer became the consultative president after he left office. Now he will resume the actual management and take over the company in crises and the current Group CEO Caille "focus his attention on daily affairs." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Traders say that the top personnel change of Adecco once again puts the company under pressure to sell. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> At 40 minutes past 9, Adecco shares dropped by 3.6%, becoming a little stable after the big drop at the opening quotation. On the Swiss stock market at the same time the big quotation stood at a 20.3 rise. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Adecco's shares fell into a turmoil after it announced on Monday that the publishing of its annual financial statements would be postponed. </seg>
