<hl>
<seg id=1> Japan Decides to Strike Budget Balance within 10 Years </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP in Tokyo on 16th) Japan's Finance Minister Sadakazu Tanigaki said today that he is fully confident that the world's second largest economy will get rid of a "financial crisis" and the finance will be rectified within 10 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Sadakazu Tanigaki says the total deficit of the central and local governments has reached 5% of Japan's GDP. If an average of 0.5% could be reduced each year, the deficit would be removed in 10 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> He told a group of journalists:" Japan's financial situation is still in crisis. </seg>
<seg id=5> We are the worst among major industrial countries in terms of (financial) circulation and reserves." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Japan decides to turn "original deficit" into "original surplus" by March 2014 --- It will be a multi-level financial balance for the first time in over 2 decades. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> This is the first time for the administration headed by Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi to put forward a clear goal for Japan to get "original surplus" again. In this circumstance, tax transcendence does not include the expenditures for paying back debts. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The last such surplus occurred in the year before March 1992. The 6-year-long surplus ended thence. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
