</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Shinsei Bank, taken over and reshaped by the American Investment Fund - Ripplewood Holding, will, for the first time, issue 242 million shares for the domestic investors in Japan and 188 million shares for overseas investors. </seg>
<seg id=4> The price for the first open issuing will be determined on February 9. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Shinsei Bank has also prepared 36.3 million shares for possible excess purchase, for possibly some subscriptions might not be realized. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The predecessor of Shinsei Bank was Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd. which became state-owned after bankruptcy in 1998. The reshaped Shinsei Bank already offers retail financial service. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The net profit of Shinsei Bank in the year by the end of March 2003 is expected to hit 65 billion Japanese Yen (613 million USD), a 22.6% growth over the previous year. Its ordinary profit is 60 billion Japanese Yen, a 76.5% growth; its total business income is 175 billion Japanese Yen, a 13% decline. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Shinsei Bank also indicates that its total bad obligation was 132.3 billion Japanese Yen, less than 154.2 billion 3 months ago. </seg>
</p>
