<hl>
<seg id=1> Shrinking Workforce to Knock Economic Output in EU, Japan </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP in Davos, Switzerland on 19th) The European Union's share of global economic output is reduced almost half by 2050 as its workforce shrinks, according to a study report published today by the World Economic Forum (WEF) and US consultancy firm Watson Wyatt Worldwide. </seg>
<seg id=3> By contrast the plenty of labor in such developing countries such as India and China should help to promote economic growth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Sammans, a managing director at the WEF, said "Economic output is determined by labour force growth and productivity rates," </seg>
<seg id=5> In countries where labor force is in serious short supply, commodities and labor supply probably cannot meet the needs and living standards." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> A report entitled "Living happier ever after: the economic implications of aging societies" points out that because of the prolonging of people's lives due to medical progress, the retirees, in relation to labor force, will continue to increase(especially in the developed countries), which finally will exercise immediate impact on economic production. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> A statement in response to the research report points out that "Suppose the current vital statistics and economic trends keep unchanged. By 2050 the proportion of EU in the world economic output value will be reduced from the present 18% to 10%." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The statement also warns "that the proportion of Japan will shrink from 8% to 4%." </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="AFC20040119.0009" sysid="che">
<hl>
<seg id=1> The Damage of Artistic Works by The Israeli Ambassador in Sweden Gave Rise to The Diplomatic Dispute between The Two Countries. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (AFP in Stockholm on 18th) A work of art in memory of a Palestinian suicidal bomb attacker in the Swedish History Museum was damaged by the Israeli ambassador Mazel in Sweden. It has given rise to a dispute which has developed into a diplomatic strife due to the intervention by Israeli Prime Minister Sharon. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Ambassador Mazel visited Stockholm Museum last Friday when he saw a work of art on show which portrays a suicidal attacker in Haifa in October last year. He deliberately damaged it, for which he expelled by the museum authority. This has led to a diplomatic conflict between Israel and Sweden. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Israel demands that Sweden remove this exhibit, which was turned down by Sweden. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The event has been extensively covered by Swedish press. </seg>
<seg id=6> The exhibition is part of an international Conference sponsored by the Swedish government on racial massacre. Israel will also attend the conference. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The on-the-spot video-tape shows the Israeli ambassador tearing down the spotlight of the conference hall and throwing it into water, resulting in the short circuit of the artistic work. Afterwards, the museum president ordered that Ambassador Mazel leave the museum. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Today Israeli Prime Minister Sharon supported Mazel, which resulted the event developed into an all-round diplomatic dispute. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The work of art on display is chiefly a ship named "White Snow" sailing on sea. On the stem is a picture of smiling Hanadi Jaradat which serves as the sail. </seg>
<seg id=10> Hanadi was a Palestine lawyer on probation who lived in Israel and whose younger brother had been killed by an Israeli bomb. To avenge her brother she launched a suicidal bomb attack last October in the northern Israeli city of Haifa, killing 21 Israelis and causing a new round of Israel vs Palestine conflicts. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Mazel said: "I cannot bear to see this picture. It is a great hurt to the victims' family members of Haifa bombing. As the Israeli ambassador, I cannot be aloof and indifferent about the picture which stand facts on their head." </seg>
</p>
