<DOC docid="DPP20030930.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> On September 28, this Party of ours spent its 17th birthday. </seg>
<seg id=2> The Democratic Progressive Party, 17 years of age, has upheld its ideal of democracy since its birth and is now filled with the power of reform and progress. </seg>
<seg id=3> It is because we have been on the side of democracy and reform that we have won the trust of the Taiwan people. It is because of this that the responsibilities and missions we bear for the future become even more grave and great. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Three years ago we took over the load of ruling the country. The past ruling parties in the 1990s had the constitution revised 6 times with a tortuous way. </seg>
<seg id=5> In 1991 overall re-election of the parliament was held; in 1994 the president was directly elected; in 1997 the provincial government organizations were frozen; in 2000 the National Assembly became non permanent. The series of constitution revisions are the legality trail of Taiwan people in intensifying sovereignty and democracy. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> If we regard the direct election of the president in 1996 as the most significant sign to show that Taiwan has become a democracy with independent sovereignty, this country "in its integrity" is already over 10 years old. </seg>
<seg id=7> After 10 years of practice we should ponder what to pursue next as a democracy with independent sovereignty. </seg>
<seg id=8> We must say that at the next stage we should further pursue more profound democracy and more efficient constitutional government system. Only by doing this can we lead the Taiwan people in confronting severe challenges of the new century. </seg>
</p>
