<DOC docid="PD20031123.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> The American government announced on November 18 that it imposes quota limit on 3 imported Chinese fabrics of knit fabrics, bras and dressing gowns. </seg>
<seg id=2> At a time when China is making persistent efforts to promote the Sino-American trade cooperation, this trade protectionism measure by US is unavoidably disappointing. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Today when economic globalization is progressing fast, the reimposing of limit on Chinese textiles by the US government is out of accord with the times. </seg>
<seg id=4> First, this abuse of "quota" measure hinders the implementation of the WTO principle of free trade. </seg>
<seg id=5> Talking in a high-sounding way about "free trade" on the one hand, US resorts to underhand means by imposing "quotas" and builds the trade barrier again. Does it not seem too arbitrary and unfair? </seg>
<seg id=6> Secondly, the "quota" hinders the positive development of the Sino-American economic and trade relations. </seg>
<seg id=7> Since China and US arrived at an agreement about China's accession to WTO in 1999, the American export to China has grown by 15% each year on an average. </seg>
<seg id=8> From January to September this year the American export to China grew by 26.2% compared with the same period last year. </seg>
<seg id=9> In the past 2 years the American export of textile raw materials and finished products to China grew by a big margin. </seg>
<seg id=10> In fact today's China is the one to which the US export grows fastest in the world. </seg>
</p>
