<DOC docid="PD20040101.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> After a dispute as long as half a year, the advance unit of Japan Self Defense Forces finally left for Iraq at the end of 2003. </seg>
<seg id=2> This is the first time after the Second World War for Japan to send its troops overseas. </seg>
<seg id=3> It reflects the will of Japan to become a political and military power. It also indicates a change of the defense strategy of Japan. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The reason why this movement of Japan Self Defense Forces is conspicuous is that it is not an isolated event. </seg>
<seg id=5> Taking advantage of the Afghani war, Japan made a breakthrough in sending its Self Defense Forces to other countries. Also by taking advantage of the Korean Peninsula issue, Japan passed "Emergency Legislation" which leaves foreshadowing for the Self Defense Forces to take pre-emptive actions. Recently Koizumi's Cabinet has passed "the Essential Plan of Assisting Iraq Reconstruction Projects," which leaves foreshadowing for sending the soldiers to Iraq. </seg>
<seg id=6> Step by step Japan has broken through the limit set by Japan's peace constitution and has sent its troops to the overseas battlefields. </seg>
<seg id=7> Besides, Japan is planning to revise the "Nation's Basic Defense Framework" in 2004 so as to make its sending troops overseas legalized and permanent. It also plans to establish a non-provisional "permanent troops" for the purpose of operation in other countries. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> At the same time the Japanese cabinet, on the pretext of the so-called "North Korean missile threat", has made the decision to start mapping out its missile defensive system in early 2004. It has also introduced from US the "standard missile-3" and the "patriot missile-3" in order to intercept those missiles outside or returning to atmosphere. So a double missile intercepting network has been formed. </seg>
<seg id=9> It is not difficult to figure out that Japan Self Defense Forces is developing towards a regular army which "combines offence with defense". The "Self Defense Forces" which "is solely engaged in defense" will cease to exist except in name. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> These acts of Japan are noticeable primarily because these military decisions are great impact on Japan's peace constitution. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="PD20040102.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Koizumi was interviewed by Japanese journalists after visiting Yasukuni Shrine and tried to justify his act. </seg>
<seg id=2> His explanation is self-contradictory and does not hold water. </seg>
<seg id=3> When asked by the journalists why he visited the Yasukuni Shrine, Koizumi answered: "Japan's peace and prosperity is realized on the basis of war victims. </seg>
<seg id=4> My visit is to appeal for Japan's peace and prosperity." </seg>
<seg id=5> Let's ask Koizumi whether or not the so-called "war victims" included such first-class war criminals as Hideki Tojo? </seg>
<seg id=6> Could it be said that the post-war peace and prosperity in Japan was also including the contribution on the basis of first-class war criminals? </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Some journalist asked him why he chose January 1 to visit the Shrine? </seg>
<seg id=8> Koizumi answered that it is a tradition in Japan to visit the Shrine on January 1. Many people visit the Shrine on this day. </seg>
<seg id=9> It is understandable that common people mourn over the death of their relatives and friends. And many mourners explicitly say that their visit is to mourn their deceased relatives and friends and they are opposed to enshrining and worshipping first-class war criminals at Yasukuni Shrine. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Chinese people are reasonable. We have always insisted that Japanese people should be separated from a few militarists and the common people should be differentiated from right-wingers. The visit of Yasukuni Shrine by the common people is not the crux of the historical problems. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
