<DOC docid="XIN20040101.0022" sysid="che">
<hl>
<seg id=1> (International) Spread of Influenza Has Reached Its Summit in America </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency in Los Angeles on Dec. 31st (Reporter Yan Liang) The US Center for Disease Control and Prevention said on 31st that the great influenza whose scale has not been seen for 30 years has reached its highest point. Large spread of the disease is found in 45 of the US 50 states and death cases caused by influenza grow drastically. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> According to the statistics of the Center by December 20th, the deaths caused by influenza already account for 7.8% of all deaths, a record high. </seg>
<seg id=4> At least 42 children have died of influenza in all over the states. Deaths of adults grow quickly, but no accurate statistics is available. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> According to experts, there are 2 reasons for the quick spread of influenza in 2003. First, the influenza virus is not the "Panama A Virus" of the past few years and the vaccines produced earlier cannot effectively prevent it. Second, two major vaccine manufacturers have reduced their production down to 83 million shots this year because of surplus last year. This has resulted in the short supply of vaccines. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Although 36,000 people die of influenza and 114,000 people are hospitalized because of the disease each year on an average, such a influenza spread that has caused social panic is rare. </seg>
<seg id=7> According to William Thompson, an expert of epidemics, this influenza is the most serious in recent 30 years. It came earlier than the past and large-scale spread occurred in many schools. There are long queues in the place where vaccines are injected against influenza. </seg>
<seg id=8> Facing such a severe situation, the American Health Ministry launched its emergency treatment center on December 19 and dispatched its expert groups to the states. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="PD20040204.001" sysid="che">
