<p>
<seg id=1> From February 7th to 8th the political celebrities from Europe, America and other world regions gathered in Munich, Germany to attend the 40th Munich Conference on Security Policy. </seg>
<seg id=2> The so-called "Munich Conference on Security Policy", founded by non-governmental persons of Germany and financially aided by the German Government, is a forum on international security issues. In recent years, especially since "September 11", it has received increasingly more attention and is lauded as "Davos Forum" in the security field. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> An important item on the agenda of the meeting is the trans-atlantic relations. </seg>
<seg id=4> The European and American political figures said at or after the conference that the two sides are striving to remove the shadow from the relations between the two sides brought about by the Iraqi War and are working hard to return to the track of cooperation. </seg>
<seg id=5> Bertram, director of Berlin Institute for International Politics and Security, said this is a meeting to mend the relations between Europe and America and both sides wish to draw close. </seg>
<seg id=6> In terms of Europe-American relations, good news from the Conference goes that Europe and America need to resume dialogues, to give careful consideration to the common tasks confronting the two sides and to find the interest converging point needed for the accomplishment of these common tasks. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Compared with the Conference held last year, this year's session is free from the smell of gunpowder and the position of the two sides come closer. </seg>
<seg id=8> The "Old Europe" represented by France and Germany, though still brood on the Iraqi War launched by US, says that they will "look forward". </seg>
<seg id=9> The German Foreign Minister Fischer said at the Conference: Although we hold different views about the war, we must jointly ensure that peace is achieved in the post-war Iraq. For this we must look forward. </seg>
<seg id=10> He also remarked that Germany will not block NATO from playing a direct role in Iraq although it won't send any troops to Iraq. </seg>
</p>
