<DOC docid="PD20040220.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> The talk between Pakistani and Indian officials was held in Islamabad from February 16th to 18th. The hope of peace rose again on the south Asian subcontinent. </seg>
<seg id=2> The officials of the 2 countries decided the schedule and agenda of the future talk and build up a mechanism for sustainable dialogues. This marks the restart of the Pakistan-Indian dialogue process after 2 years of suspension, laying a foundation for the settlement of all unsolved issues including Kashmir dispute. It embodies the valuable wish for peace of both sides. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Before this talk most of analysts hold cautious attitudes to the prospects of the peace process, although the relationship between the 2 countries had been warmed up by a series of good-will actions of both sides. </seg>
<seg id=4> It is small wonder. Recalling the sudden rise and abrupt fall in the Pakistan-Indian relationship, nobody can guarantee that the sunshine on today's talk table won't turn into thunder and lightning on the border tomorrow. </seg>
<seg id=5> However, the foreign secretary Riaz Khokhar of Pakistani State Council announced with a smile on 18 the joint statement of the 2 countries which immediately spread the optimistic mood all over the place. It made those who are concerned with the south Asian situation brighten up. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> First of all the schedule determined for the talk is very feasible. The two sides not only clearly know the specific time and agenda of the talk but also different talk levels are decided in proportion to the importance of the specific topics. </seg>
<seg id=7> Secondly, the directly dialogues between the leaders of the 2 countries brought the talk on failed during the Agra summit in July 2001. The two sides draw a lesson from it and take the mode of dialogues by "step by step". The talks level will be launched from low to high in order to prepare fully for the high level dialogues. </seg>
<seg id=8> Thirdly, the two countries, after experiencing ups and downs in the relationship between the 2 countries, unanimously make it clear that war is not a good method to settle the conflict and both sides should keep away from war. This consensus has laid a good foundation for the future leaders of the 2 countries to reach an understanding of "no war forever between Pakistan and India." </seg>
</p>
