<DOC docid="PD20040221.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> After "September 11" incident the American President Bush put forward the "pre-emptive" strategy in June 2002 and began to use it in the US foreign relations. And in March last year he fought the first "pre-emptive" war in Iraq. </seg>
<seg id=2> The "pre-emptive" idea not only goes against the principle of international law which takes "mutual respect of sovereignty and territorial integrity" as the kernel but also will inevitably give rise to the dangerous imitation effects. The international order will suffer new turmoil because of this. </seg>
<seg id=3> In the early days when the "pre-emptive" theory was proposed, some American political celebrities asked this question: What if other countries follow the example?" </seg>
<seg id=4> As expected, more and more countries clamor to overwhelm others by "pre-emptive" means. The "pre-emptive" troops keep growing. </seg>
<seg id=5> This is a new trend worth our attention and study. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In the very month when Bush put forward his "pre-emptive" strategy, the Prime Minister of Australia Howard was the first to voice his support. </seg>
<seg id=7> He said that once we have reliable information about terrorist attack against Australia, Australia will adopt the "pre-emptive" strategy and will take military actions in the neighboring countries at all costs. </seg>
<seg id=8> He even suggest that the "pre-emptive" principle be included into the UN Charter. He thinks it is necessary to make amendments to the UN Charter and give the right of "pre-emptive" attack to all countries so as to crack down on terrorists and those countries that support terrorist activities. </seg>
<seg id=9> In northeast Asia the Japanese Ministry of Defense proposed as early as in July 1999 in its Defense White Paper that Japan may launch "pre-emptive" attacks against foreign bases when facing missile attack or before any military invasion. </seg>
<seg id=10> After the Iraqi War, Japan's cry for "pre-emptive" strategy has caused a clamor. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="PD20040224.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Recently, there have been many comments on America's present policies towards Africa in international public opinions. </seg>
<seg id=2> On America's "Foreign Policy in Focus" published in January this year, there is an article entitled "Africa Policy Outlook 2004". The article holds that the foreign policies of Bush Administration in the past year have brought about direct or indirect negative influence on Africa. The full concerns of America were about the Anti-terrorist war and the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction, especially US was involved in Iraq, therefore, its attention to Afirica has been diverted much more. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> People still remember that to display its concern for Africa, Bush Administration last year worked out "the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief" and promised to provide Africa with 3 billion USD at least each year. </seg>
<seg id=4> In July last year Bush visited Senegal, South Africa, Botswana, Uganda and Nigeria and promised to assist African countries with 15 billion USD to prevent AIDS and 100 million USD to fight against terrorist activities. He also announced some assisting Africa programs including Emergency Food Assistance Plan and Education Aid Plan. </seg>
<seg id=5> These assistance programs were once welcomed by African countries and won many international praises. </seg>
<seg id=6> However, a year has passed and US has not shown any sign of implementing them. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Africa needs assistance badly. </seg>
<seg id=8> After the world entered the new century, Africa faces various development challenges. In order to realize "the Century Development Goals" worked out by the UN in 2002, i.e. to reduce hunger and poverty and promote health and education, Africa has set up its "African Union" whose mission it is to plan and coordinate African affairs in a unified way and has drawn up the "African New Partnership Program for Development" aiming to promote the development of the countries. But because of the weak economic basis, fund has always been in short supply. </seg>
<seg id=9> UN has appealed many times to the developed countries to use 0.7% of their GDP to provide official help to the least developed countries. </seg>
<seg id=10> However, the American official aid accounts for only 0.1% of its GDP, far below the UN demand. It is the last one on the list of the contributing countries. </seg>
</p>
