<DOC docid="PD20040226.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Recently, there has been a hot topic discussed by the European public: Is the "3 magnate" summit of German Prime Minister Schroeder, the French President Chirac and the British Prime Minister Blair going to be increasingly systematic and regular? </seg>
<seg id=2> Public opinion calls the "big three" of Germany, France and Britain "a new troika" of EU. The relationship of the 3 nations is called a "new triangle" affair. </seg>
<seg id=3> "New triangle" is a new thing and we have to wait and see how it will develop. But whichever angle you judge it, "new triangle" in general is help for the process of European integration and for Europe to play its important role on the international arena as a pole of the multiple world. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> A survey of the 100 year history of Europe will tell you that a basic characteristic of the German-France-British triangle is that British and France jointly contain and resist Germany. </seg>
<seg id=5> The two world wars are the evidence. </seg>
<seg id=6> During the cold war East and West Germany were sandwiched between the Warsaw Pact and NATO. </seg>
<seg id=7> After the cold war is over, the unified Germany is stronger; the power frame in west Europe is out of balance. France is more dubious and as a result the "German-France Axis" was once out of operation. Therefore Britain and France come closer with an intention still to contain Germany. </seg>
<seg id=8> But in recent years, with the restart of the "German-France Axis" and the fierce conflicts between the ideas of world monopolarization and world multipolarization, great dissensions occurred inside EU over the Iraqi issue: </seg>
<seg id=9> "The Old Europe" represented by Germany and France and "the New Europe" represented by Britain and Poland are poles apart in their stands on the Iraqi issue. </seg>
<seg id=10> This split occurred accidentally at a time when EU is going to carry out its largest expansion in history. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="PD20040227.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Egyptian President Mubarak made a speech in Cairo a few days ago on the reform of Arab countries, criticizing the outside world for imposing one mode of reform on the Arab countries. He also warned that the attempt runs counter to its desire and is no conducive to the security and stability of the Middle East region. </seg>
<seg id=2> He believes that reform measures should conform to the specific conditions and capabilities of the respective countries. A single reform mode ignores the cultural backgrounds, social customs and religious features of different countries. </seg>
<seg id=3> At the same he points out that the Arab countries welcome outside help in their reform process, but this effort should recognize specific conditions of different countries and respect their wishes so as to promote the reform process of the Arab countries in politics, economy and culture. </seg>
