<DOC docid="UN20040101.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Since the delegation of the Security Council visited the 6 countries in west Africa at the end of last June, inspiring changes have taken place in the general situation of the whole region although one or two countries have experienced some relapses. </seg>
<seg id=2> We are glad to notice that the Sierra Leone government has made positive progress in promoting the capability of the army and the police, intensifying the control of the country's diamond, preparing for the election of local governments, etc. The UN Mission in Sierra Leone is gradually reducing in its size according to the plan. </seg>
<seg id=3> What also inspries us is that, with the disposition of UN Mission in Liberia, Liberia is getting rid of the influence of the long-time war and is embarking on the road to restoration and reconstruction. </seg>
<seg id=4> Guinea-Bissau has made headways in its political process and the transitional government has promised to hold legislature election in March this year. </seg>
<seg id=5> The peace process in Cote d'Ivoire is taking a turn for the better after some setbacks. All the sides have promised to implement "Linas-Marcoussis Accord" and "the new army" announces to return to the national reconciliation government. The Security Council is considering to send peace-keepers to the country. </seg>
<seg id=6> We are looking forward to the decision of the Security Council in this regard as soon as possible. </seg>
<seg id=7> The secretariat, the west African Economic Community and other related sides are working hard to settle the problems of small arms, mercenary troops, children soldiers, etc. and they have made progress. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> While acknowledging the above progress completely, we should see that the general situation in the region of west Africa still has its fragile sides. Especially, due to geographical and historical factors, the countries in this region are closely linked and the situation in one country influences another. The turmoil in one country may spread to its neighbors and even to the whole region. </seg>
<seg id=9> Therefore, as suggested by the Security Council report, when trying to solve the issues in West Africa, the international community including the Security Council should persist in a comprehensive and all-sided strategy, i.e. endeavoring to solve the cross-border issues; Meanwhile, it should actively help the relevant countries, the African Union, the West African Economic Community and other regional and sub-regional organizations to enhance their capability in preventing and settling conflicts. </seg>
</p>
