<DOC docid="UN20040101.002" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> We have a consensus that children are the future of the world. </seg>
<seg id=2> We are obliged to provide them with the best and optimum conditions so as to facilitate their life, study, growth, maturing and success. </seg>
<seg id=3> However, what is regretful is that in today's world hundreds of thousands of kids are still suffering from the injury of armed conflicts. </seg>
<seg id=4> What they are experiencing are turmoil and backwardness. what they are witnessing are violence and destruction. What they are suffering are injuries and abuse. What they feel are sad and helpless. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Therefore, it is the important obligation of the international community to keep children from the injuries of armed conflicts. </seg>
<seg id=6> All countries, especially those involved in the conflicts, should do their utmost for this purpose. </seg>
<seg id=7> We are glad to see that in recent years UN has adopted a series of measures in protecting kids from armed conflicts and has made headways. </seg>
<seg id=8> The Security Council has passed 4 resolutions in succession of 1261 (1999), 1314 (2000), 1379 (2001) and 1460 (2003), providing an important frame for the work of children protection. </seg>
<seg id=9> The peace-keeping activities of UN take the protection of children as their important mission in some regions, including appointment of advisors for children protection and giving full consideration to the special needs of children in the process of helping the countries to demilitarization, demobilization and the plan to return to society. </seg>
<seg id=10> Some peace accords promoted by UN or with its participation also include clauses on children protection. </seg>
</p>
