<DOC docid="UN20040101.003" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> National reconciliation is the important condition for peace and stability in the regions after conflicts. </seg>
<seg id=2> After the conflict is over, the peaceful situation cannot really be consolidated and the conflict flames may even be rekindled if the sides concerned cannot forget their past grudges and give up their past resentments. </seg>
<seg id=3> Under many circumstances to achieve national reconciliation after a conflict needs joint endeavor from all sides and at the same time requires the international community, especially UN, to provide support and assistance. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> For years UN has played a helpful role in promoting the process of national reconciliation in pro-conflict countries and has accumulated much experience. We think that generally speaking UN has to correctly handle 3 major relationships hereinafter in order to successfully help the post-conflict countries to achieve national reconciliation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> It should integrate immediate needs with long-term goals. </seg>
<seg id=6> National reconciliation normally calls for a considerable process and it can hardly be accomplished in one move. </seg>
<seg id=7> There should be different priorities at different phases. </seg>
<seg id=8> The first thing to do in achieving national reconciliation is to make the former fighters to "say good-bye to arms" so as to create an environment of safety. </seg>
<seg id=9> At this stage it is very important to disarm the former fighters and help them demobilize and return to society. </seg>
</p>
