<DOC docid="UN20040119.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> In recent years small arms have arrested the close attention of the international community. </seg>
<seg id=2> This indicates that all the parties concerned are increasingly aware of the harmful accumulation and contraband of small arms on the stability, post-war reconstruction and social development in the regions and countries involved. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Fortunately, UN has taken a series of effective actions in order to solve the problem. </seg>
<seg id=4> In 2001 "Firearms Protocol" as an attachment to "The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime" and the UN "Program of Action" on small arms have been successively concluded. </seg>
<seg id=5> They provide legal and policy basis for the settlement of small arms problem and demonstrate the determination of the international community in cracking down on illegal trade of small arms. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In the past 3 years the international community has made great progress in promoting the implementation of "Firearm Protocol" and "Program of Action". Especially the successful convening in 2003 of the first UN biennial conference on small arms has given new impetus to the all-round and earnest implementation of "Program of Action". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> According to No. 58/241 resolution passed at this UN General Assembly, a working group will be set up to negotiate over an international document to identify and investigate illegal small arms. This undoubtedly will step up the endeavor of the international community to crack down on illegal trade of small arms. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Likewise, the UN Security Council has paid more and more attention to the small arms issue. It has held many discussions exclusively on the issue and passed relevant statements and resolutions of the chairman. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> In addition, the Security Council has stressed the importance of the small arms issue while discussing how to protect civilians, women and children etc. series issues in conflicts. </seg>
</p>
