<DOC docid="XIN20040114.0229" sysid="che">
<hl>
<seg id=1> (Archaeological Discovery) 31 Qin Tombs Discovered in Fengxing County of Shanxi Province </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency in Xi'an on January 15th (Tie Ma) Historians used to believe that the palace area at Sunjia Nantou Village in Fengxiang County of Shaanxi Province was not the place for sacrificial activities until Qin people moved their capital to Yongcheng. But Shaanxi Archaeological Research Institute has recently discovered 31 Qin tombs in the palace area and the discovery may change this allegation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> For an enterprise in Baoji City would purchase land to build a factory on the ruins, Shaanxi Archaeological Research Institute carried out an archaeological survey of the place. In the about 20,000 square meters area which was anxious to use were discovered 31 Qin tombs in the period from Western Zhou to the Spring & Autumn Period. </seg>
<seg id=4> The excavation by Shaanxi Yongcheng Archaeological Team unearthed over 40 pieces of bronze and pottery relics. </seg>
<seg id=5> In one of such Qin tombs were found 2 coffins in an outer coffin. Beside the tomb is a subordinate pit with 2 horses. </seg>
<seg id=6> From the tomb were unearthed 15 pieces of bronze and pottery relics. The bronzewares include Ding, basins, axes, etc. </seg>
<seg id=7> The bronze Ding is exquisite in workmanship and decoration. It keeps the style of Western Zhou bronzewares. </seg>
<seg id=8> Judging from the buried articles, the owner of the tomb was an aristocrat in late Western Zhou. </seg>
<seg id=9> Experts inferred that there should be a group of ancient tombs nearby. </seg>
<seg id=10> The accidental discovery is of great historic value for the study of capital moving of the Qin and for the study of the layout of Yongcheng in the Qin-Han Dynasty period. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Associate Researcher of Shaanxi Archaeological Research Institute and Leader of Yongcheng Archaeological Team Tian Yaqi says that people in the history circles used to think that the palace area at Sunjia Nantou Village was not the place for sacrificial activities until the capital of the Qin was moved to Yongcheng. </seg>
<seg id=12> The discovery, however, proves that this place had been a manor estate granted by the emperor long before the capital was moved to Yongcheng and it had undergone prosperity and decline many times. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
