<p>
<seg id=4> The non-profit organization "Joint Venture Silicon Valley Network" said in its annual report "2004 Index of Silicon Valley" that the unemployment rate in the Silicon Valley region between the 2nd season of 2002 and 2nd season of 2003 dropped from the previous year's 10% to the present 5%. </seg>
<seg id=5> The report predicts that the unemployment rate will continue to fall with the recovery of hi-tech industry. </seg>
<seg id=6> Presently the economic development of the Silicon Valley confronts the following challenge: large number of well trained hi-tech workers are needed to fill up the new job vacancies. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> The report says that of all hi-tech trades in the Silicon Valley, the bio-technological industry has the lowest unemployment rate and its recovery trend is the most obvious. The risk investment amount attracted by the bio-technological industry in the Valley is for the first time at the same level with that of the computer software industry. </seg>
<seg id=8> The report holds that the bio-technological industry will play an increasingly important role in the economic development of the Silicon Valley. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The report also shows that the average pay of the employees in the Silicon Valley fell for the 3rd consecutive year from the 2nd season of 2002 to the 2nd season of 2003. But the decline rate went down from 6% in the previous year to 1.5% at present. </seg>
<seg id=10> The average annuity of the labor force in the Silicon Valley, still a wealthy place in the US, is 62,400 USD, 60% higher than the average of American labor force. </seg>
<seg id=11> However, the consumption level of the region is 47% higher than the national average. </seg>
