<seg id=4> The low exchange rate of USD will provide US with larger room for economic development and more job opportunities, which is extremely obvious in the manufacturing industry. </seg>
<seg id=5> At the same time the devaluation of USD makes US products more competitive on the domestic and world markets. This is conducive for US to compensate its adverse balance of trade. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Bur experts also believe the weak USD will bring about negative effect on America too. </seg>
<seg id=7> First of all the American stock market may continue to go down and the value of various investments falls. Foreign investors may withdraw their funds for fear of further USD devaluation. Secondly, imported goods are more and more expensive, resulting in the decline of American people's livelihood. Thirdly, large-scale devaluation of USD may give rise to turbulence in trade and finance. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> But the devaluation of USD brings more serious blows to Europe, Japan and Canada. </seg>
<seg id=9> The decline of USD exchange rate exercises more pressure on the export of European commodities. This means European economy faces the danger of an all-round decline. </seg>
