<hl>
<seg id=1> (International) Denmark Promulgates New Act to Restrict Immigrants </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Xinhua News Agency in Stockholm on January 28th) News from Copenhagen says that Danish government has submitted to the congress a new act to restrict immigrants. </seg>
<seg id=3> According to the act, those Danish-born children from the family of foreign immigrants will no longer enjoy the right of acquiring Danish nationality automatically. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The proposed act is the latest of many measures adopted by Denmark to restrict immigrants since Rasmussen, Leader of Danish Liberal Party, began to work as prime minister in November 2001. </seg>
<seg id=5> It is reported that the act is very likely to be passed by the congress, for the Liberal Party has the support of the right-wing Danish People's Party on the issue of immigration. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The law requires that the Danish-born children of foreigners, when grown up, to apply for nationality like other immigrants, instead of acquiring nationality automatically. </seg>
<seg id=7> Those immigrants who have already acquired nationality will be deprived of it if they commit crimes that pose great menace to the society. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In the past 2 years Danish government has promulgated a series of restriction policies, including limitation of issuing long-term residence permits and restriction of immigrant's bringing their family members to Denmark. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The unfriendly attitude of Danish government towards immigrants has reduced the number of refugees from 14,347 in 1993 to 3,500 in 2003. </seg>
<seg id=10> The image of Denmark as a liberal and human right country is therefore spoiled. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040219.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> For less than a month after the spring festival, there have been 3 extraordinarily large safety accidents, each of which resulted in more than 10 deaths. </seg>
<seg id=2> The high frequency and the heavy casualties are lamenting. </seg>
<seg id=3> Several months before this, the blowout of natural gas oil pipes in Chongqing, gas explosions on several coal mines and frequently occurred traffic accidents had caused several hundred deaths. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> China is vast and densely populated and the disaster probability is greater than in other countries. A disaster often results in dozens or even hundreds of deaths. This is an objective and helpless fact. </seg>
<seg id=5> But common sense tells us that the death accidents in China are still too frequent. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Of various disasters, fires, coal mine explosions, explosions of fireworks factories and passenger transport accidents are the greatest in number. </seg>
<seg id=7> This gives expression to 2 facts at least. First, safety measures in these aspects are the weakest. Second, people have not drawn lessons from these tragedies. As a result these accidents keep repeating themselves. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In the past when Singapore was experiencing high economic growth rates, there also occurred serious fires, which still remain to be tragic memories and have swiftly enhanced Singapore's  precaution consciousness of security in the public places. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> China is likewise at an unusual stage of fast economic growth and big social transition. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040221.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> It is occasionally heard that foreign housemaids working in the locality accidentally fall off buildings. Although the number of such accidents is not abnormally high, such fall-off-building accidents run much counter to the nature of household work in which casualty should be low, considering the relatively safe environment of house-maid work. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=2> Data show that from January 1999 to June 2003 altogether 99 housemaids from different countries died from falling off buildings. </seg>
<seg id=3> Behind the figure are broken families who are waiting for daughters or mothers to return home. Behind it are tragedies that may well have been avoided and is the orientation of our endeavor to do our best to reduce the regretful figure to the minimum. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to the announcement recently released by the Indonesian Embassy, 96 Indonesian housemaids have died when they worked in Singapore since 1999 and some of them died from falling off the building while working in high buildings. </seg>
<seg id=5> Facing that the Indonesian government has now and then expressed their resentment over such accidents, we have also worked out new regulations many times to exercise stricter control of the quality of Indonesian housemaid in the place so as to ensure their safety. However, the problem remains unsettled. The relationship between Singapore and Indonesia in inevitably perplexed by the housemaid issue. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> What profoundly confuses people is the fact that, compared with the casualties of foreign laborers on construction sites, the casualties of housemaids' falling off the building are higher. This gives food for thought and it is necessary to study the background and causes of such accidents. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040221.002" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Mr. Chen Kongli, a worldly famous expert on Taiwan issues in Mainland China, recently published his new book "Observing Taiwan". </seg>
<seg id=2> Most of the essays included in the book were written after March 2000 when the substitution of political parties took place in Taiwan for the first time. They reflect the author's observation and reflections, up to the time when Chen Shui-bian put forward his "one country on either side" theory, on internal situation in Taiwan and the cross-strait relationship during the period of the author's "not only listening to what he says but also watching what be does." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The articles written 2 years ago cannot be published until now. This shows that the screening procedure on the mainland is complicated and long for the articles related to Taiwan studies. It shows more clearly that it is not easy for "Observing Taiwan" to be accessible to readers. </seg>
<seg id=4> For a long time Mr. Chen Kongli has always been realistic and factual in observing and studying issues related to Taiwan. He has never let himself be confined by subjectively preset political frames and has endeavored to explore and find unique viewpoints. </seg>
<seg id=5> After reading the book it is even more profoundly impressed by this characteristic of the book. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> After early 80s of the last century Taiwan studies became "a popular subject" and many research institutions appeared. All kinds of scholars and experts show up prominently. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Overseas people normally divide the mainland research institutions of Taiwan studies into Northern School and Southern School. </seg>
<seg id=8> The Northern School, whose stand is near to the official position, is unyielding in remarks. It displays the aggressive color of the hawk in some specific historical periods or on some important of developments political conjuncture. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> And the Southern School of Taiwan study institutions are mostly scattered south of the Yangtze River including Shanghai, Fujian and other places. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040222.005" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> The Japanese Prime Minister Junichiro Koizumi is accused by the Japanese media as overstatement on his "educational background" of "studying in London for 2 years". </seg>
<seg id=2> The Japanese "Post Newsweek" proves to the Dean's Office of London University that during his 9 month stay in Britain Junichiro Koizumi only attended several courses as a visitor and did not get any academic degree. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> This scandal is covered or reprinted by Chinese media, large or small, to the immense gratification of the compatriots. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Indeed, the prime minister of such a country goes so far as to fabricate his educational background and cheat his own people. </seg>
<seg id=5> It is an even greater disgrace especially when it happened in the "imperialist" Japan. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> However, if we approach it from a different angle, perhaps we may see some positive meaning out of this scandal. </seg>
<seg id=7> And this something positive is something we are lacking in and is what we need to improve. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In recent years we have been advocating "honesty" and have been trying to "construct a sunshine government", respect the public's "right to know" and promote the "transparency" of administration. But there is still a far cry between fact and ideal. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Please think, the "adulterate" diploma of a prime minister is not something of magnitude. However, it is exposed by mass media which refuse to give up half way. </seg>
<seg id=10> In such a country, is there anything else that can not be "sunshine"? </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040223.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> In evening gatherings of the election campaign, different camps would use sight-seeing buses to take the masses to the meeting place. But the recent situation is such that the evening gathering in favor of Chen Shui-bian and Annette Lu is obviously less busy than that in favor of Lien and Soong. </seg>
<seg id=2> Not long ago the Taiwan President Chen Shui-bian was shouting "we will be elected" at a campaign meeting in northern Taiwan, when half of the participants refused to echo him. It turned out that most of the people in the place have relatives who have invested on the mainland and they felt uneasy when the "three direct links" across the Taiwan straits had been delayed again and again and Chen's financial policy had yielded little results. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Except for surprises, when Taiwan election comes to the count down, we can suppose that Chen and Lu will fail, judging from the signs of public opinion polls and illegal betting. </seg>
<seg id=4> Except for sensational unexpectations such as major split or more ugly scandal of pan-blue, Chen Shui-bian who succeeded Lee Teng-hui after arduous struggle has proved that he could not effectively win over the support of the people in the past 4 year. Instead, black gold, the low-taste role and performance of pan-green have weakened the confidence of their supporters. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> How will Beijing treat the pan-blue forces which may assume power again? </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The first thing we should understand is that the pan-blue army which may assume power again is no longer the pure monolithic Kuomintang, but a combination of blue and orange and whether or not the inner tradition has merged with the nativist. </seg>
<seg id=7> The close cooperation in the election period should be not considered as the inevitable future relationship. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> If it is likely to be elected, it will surely need considerable time to conduct internal regrouping. The legislature election which comes immediately afterwards at the end of the year will make it difficult for the Lien -Soong Administration to make major changes on the cross-strait relations. </seg>
<seg id=9> Unless it is aware that the improvement of the cross-strait relations will add to its political points and it is sure to accomplish results in a short period of time. The most important thing is to enable the public to feel the results. </seg>
<seg id=10> With this background in view, Beijing should slow down its action of pushing for reunification so as to leave enough time for the Lien-Soong "traditional blue camp" to consolidate their control of the internal affairs. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040226.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> More than half a century has passed since July 1945 when US carried out its first nuclear explosion in New Mexico and August of the same year when it dropped 2 A-bombs on Japan. </seg>
<seg id=2> Although the 2 superpowers of the USA and the Soviet Union had piled up in their arms race the nuclear weapons enough to destroy the whole world, both came to realize the danger of a nuclear war and avoided pushing down on the nuclear button. </seg>
<seg id=3> After the Soviet Union disintegrated, the world entered into a post-cold war era and the danger of a large nuclear war was eliminated. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> But at the same time nuclear proliferation has increased instead of being decreased. </seg>
<seg id=5> Such proliferation embodies itself in 2 aspects. </seg>
<seg id=6> First, some countries above the intermediate level in resources and strength have tried every means to produce and possess nuclear weapon to achieve their diplomatic ends of contending with their neighbors, maintaining peace and blackmail strategy. </seg>
<seg id=7> Secondly, some non-state mass organizations, especially those Moslem extremist forces hostile to the west, are also trying by hook or by crook to lay hands on small nuclear weapons in order to carry out bloody terrorist attacks against the west at the sacrifice of large numbers of innocent people. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Such needs have given rise to brokers dealing in nuclear weapons, and the transfer of related technology and to "the nuclear black market". Their number is increasing daily and it has become an important part of the world nuclear proliferation today. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040304.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> As a descend of the Yellow Emperor who grew up in the area around the Lake area, HangJia, I still remember the rural scene and the peasants' life south of the Yangtze River. </seg>
<seg id=2> On returning to the hometown after years of separation I find that the green farmland along the Shanghai-Hangzhou Expressway is dotted with brand-new 3-storeyed buildings built by the farmers themselves and there are few peasants working in the fields. </seg>
<seg id=3> This is really surprising me and I can hardly believe that such great changes have taken place on my motherland of which I have always cherished of fond memory in foreign country. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> But recently I read on the internet some reportage and investigation reports by scholars on the rural situation which took me by surprise and shocked me. </seg>
<seg id=5> Out of my expectation there is such a dark side of rural China and Chinese peasants are leading such a humiliating, no rights and miserable life. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The long reportage entitled "Investigation into China's Countryside" written by Chen Guidi and his wife after their inquiry in the 3 provinces of Anhui, Henan and Hebei pleads on behalf of the people and has caused sensation in China's society. </seg>
<seg id=7> They draw such a conclusion from lots of facts about peasants suffering from oppression of corrupt officials and innocent people being killed: "Approaching China's countryside we feel unprecedented shock and pain. We have seen unexpected poverty, startling crimes, surprising helplessness, astonishing opposing, unforeseen silence and sorrow." </seg>
<seg id=8> This has put me into extreme grief. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040305.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> As expected the Malaysian Prime Minister Abdullah announced the day before yesterday to dissolve the parliament and the new election will be held soon. </seg>
<seg id=2> For Abdullah the on-coming election is an event of great importance. For the political situation and its trend for development, it is also of symbolic significance. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Abdullah took over power from Mahathir last November. 4 months have passed since then. </seg>
<seg id=4> In spite of this he has decided to dissolve the parliament and hold the election in advance. </seg>
<seg id=5> This contains 2 meanings at least. First, Abdullah feels satisfied with his 4 months of administration and is fully confident about the voting of electors. Secondly, he wishes to consolidate his power through this and to get rid of the shadow of Mahathir. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Undoubtedly, Abdullah's abrupt decision to hold the election shows that he has had an overall judgement of the domestic political situation. </seg>
<seg id=7> The economic situation in Malaysia is good now and there is nothing for the opposition party to publicize maliciously or to make use of. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Besides, since Abdullah took over power, he has taken some visible measures to fight corruption including the arrest and prosecution of the former Land and Cooperative Development Minister Kasitah Gaddam. These measures have won general approval and the public is now optimistic and is looking forward to the future anti-corruption acts. </seg>
<seg id=9> In the meanwhile he calls for better efficiency in civil service, which helps to promote people's trust. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040305.002" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Since its inception, the European Union has been influenced by French politics and culture in its growth and maturity. </seg>
<seg id=2> It seeks independence and self-reliance in diplomacy and differs from US in its approach and handling of international affairs. From this trend of the EU diplomatic policies, we can clearly see the shadow of France. </seg>
<seg id=3> It is because of this that the international community including China, Russia and Arab countries wish to see the rise of EU and wish to find an entirely independent force in international intercourse. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> We have to admit that since 1980s EU has been really moving towards this orientation in diplomacy. </seg>
<seg id=5> In December 1992 the EU countries reached an agreement on the Mastricht Summit that all member countries shall carry out unified diplomatic policies and speak to the outside world with one voice. </seg>
<seg id=6> But 2 years later in handling the Bosnia issue, the so-called "unified diplomatic policies" met with total failure. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> From Mastricht Summit to the present, the 10-year EU diplomacy has yielded few results. </seg>
<seg id=8> What's more, the EU diplomatic policies cannot stand the test of great events. </seg>
<seg id=9> The different attitudes adopted by the member countries towards Iraqi War not only bear out this point but also once again fully unveil the fatal political deficiencies of EU, i.e. it is easily divided and controlled by other powers. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040306.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> On February 24 President Bush announced in the White House that he will support the constitutional amendment on prohibition of homosexual marriage. </seg>
<seg id=2> This is a noticeable change of his ambiguous attitude on this issue for months and it represents a major political development in America's year of election. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The constitutional amendment on banning homosexual marriage is a very powerful political weapon in southern America which is the new headquarters of the Republican. But it also has its negative effect, i.e. this cultural dispute of great magnitude which splits public opinion will undoubtedly speed up the polarization of American politics all over the country and will further alienate the east and the west coasts dominated by liberalists. </seg>
<seg id=4> For Bush himself who repeatedly announced during the election in 2000 that he was "a uniter", not "a splitter", this is obviously an indication that his deeds run counter to his words. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Besides, the young Americans are more and more liberal on the homosexual issues. This act by Bush will harm the long-term interest of the Republican though it may yield short-term effects. </seg>
<seg id=6> The new offensive "Amendments to the Constitution" by Bush may be called "the scorched earth strategy" for the presidential election this year. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Bush adopts this strategy because, after his position is being weaken on the 2 major issues of "anti-terror" war and economy-employment, he had to open up a new battle field on the religious and cultural themes splitting the domestic public opinion. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040306.002" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> The US's attitude has remained cautions till now. </seg>
<seg id=2> In other words, because maintaining the status quo on Taiwan Strait can meet the American long-term goal of checking the mainland in strategy, US has to avoid political and military conflicts with China resulting from encouraging Taiwan independence. </seg>
<seg id=3> One can imagine that US cannot possibly deprive Taiwan of all its space for a referendum in complete conformity with Beijing's demand. But it will adopt some warning acts in view of its own interest. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Recently the American State Secretary Powell reiterated the US policy towards Taiwan and initially expressed the US stand against Taiwan independence. </seg>
<seg id=5> This declaration of attitude is interpreted by the outsiders as a check and prevention of Chen Shui-bian from being possessed by the Devil. </seg>
<seg id=6> Some American think-tankers with official background have made statements and US will send lots of spy ships to the Taiwan Strait in surveillance of the military movements on both two coasts. All this indicated indirectly that US is very much concerned about the situation in Taiwan Strait. </seg>
<seg id=7> Watching from another angle, one may find that, although US will not completely prevent Taiwan from holding a referendum according to the demand of Beijing, it feels very much worried about the uncertainties in the situation of Taiwan Strait. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> For any large and one-to-one election, only one result will come about, either Chen Shui-bian will be lucky to keep his presidency or Lien Chan will preside over the Taiwan presidential palace over again. </seg>
<seg id=9> The anxiety is that, when information and communication are not well matched, people from all circles on the mainland are not psychologically prepared for the possible victory on the part of Chen Shui-bian. </seg>
<seg id=10> If the election result is contrary to its wish, Beijing will be once again put into an unnecessary and passive predicament. </seg>
