<DOC docid="ZBN20040306.003" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> An ancient Arabic proverb goes: "One day's turmoil is worse than a thousand years' tyranny." </seg>
<seg id=2> Is this what the northeast Asian countries are worried about presently? </seg>
<seg id=3> I think the answer is probably affirmative. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> A well-known research and development center which is near Washington and is sponsored by the US government studies the 4 optional decisions on dealing with the North Korea nuclear crisis in one of its latest investigations, i.e. engagement, blocking, economic sanction and pre-emptive. </seg>
<seg id=5> The attitudes of the countries in the region towards the strategy have been the focus of this investigation. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Besides, the investigation provides an analysis of the threat posed by the North Korean nuclear program, based on the possible nuclear attack and its damage assumed by the neighbors of North Korea and on their fears. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> China and Russia hold that the danger of North Korea using nuclear weapons is low or very low while Japan and South Korea believe that the threat is considerably great. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> All the northeast Asian countries are in favor of engagement with North Korea. </seg>
<seg id=9> Japan is for blocking and other countries believe that blocking strategy is acceptable in some circumstance. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040306.004" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Singapore attaches great importance to international ranking and pays attention all the year round to various rankings of countries released by European and American agencies. </seg>
<seg id=2> Often ranking among the top countries naturally adds to our interest in this regard. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> But if you are ranked first in everything, troubles and vexations may come about. </seg>
<seg id=4> Generally speaking, our people think that if you care too much about the ranking, it seems you are afraid of losing. If you give prominence to your ranking, you seem to be arrogant. </seg>
<seg id=5> So people say we should be free and easy. The best thing is to stand aloof from worldly success. </seg>
<seg id=6> As many people scorned the rankings, there appeared an odd phenomenon: people no longer regard "the world first" as a good tiding, but rather something embarrassing. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> However, in the past one or two years, things began to change again. </seg>
<seg id=8> We feel doubtful about our country's long-term competitive power. People of all trades are worried about their jobs. </seg>
<seg id=9> With these doubts, we can no longer be free and easy when we speak. </seg>
<seg id=10> International competition is fierce. Being too free and easy may lead to the result that others may catch up. Being first in everything may become backward in everything. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
