<p>
<seg id=1> The opponents for the American 2004 presidential election have been determined: the Democratic candidate Kerry challenges the Republic President Bush. </seg>
<seg id=2> Before the general election in November they will unfold "warming up activities" such as advertising publicity, election debates. etc. </seg>
<seg id=3> They will perhaps be engaged in oral and literal battles around 3 tops of war, economy and society. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Bush holds that the war is closely associated with the state security of US. To send troops to topple Saddam and fight terror both aim to ensure the safety of US. So he has said again and again to the American public: "We are now at war." </seg>
<seg id=5> Kerry of course will point out Bush's mistake of abusing the wrong information about the weapons of mass destruction in Iraq and sending troops there. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In economy Kerry advocates that Bush's plan to reduce tax will only benefit the rich and cannot create more job opportunities. </seg>
<seg id=7> Bush shows to Kerry: Are the statistics of American economy on the rise? </seg>
<seg id=8> On social issues, e.g. relationship between male and female, Bush is against homosexual marriage and abortion and is in favor of capital punishment, while Kerry is also against homosexual marriage but is for abortion and against capital punishment. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> For Bush and Kerry, how to present their viewpoints on the 3 major issues through advertisements, TV and speeches and how to persuade the voters will be their political shows in the next 8 months. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Nevertheless, Kerry has relatively more room to show off on diplomatic issues. </seg>
</p>
