<DOC docid="ZBN20040308.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Statistics show that young people who commit suicide are mostly between 15 and 19 years old, and some are the younger between 10 to 14 old. </seg>
<seg id=2> It is generally believed that pressure of academic study is the leading cause for children and adolescents to kill themselves. However, investigations show that affection, especially love between boys and girls, and the relationship between adolescents and their parents are even more important in leading them to end up their lives. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Pressure from lessons and disappointment from expectation of course belong to the category of communication between children and their parents. </seg>
<seg id=4> Pressure resulting from going to schools of higher grade is an inevitable burden on children in their development. Sometimes the pressure comes from the adolescents themselves and mostly it is imposed on them by their parents. </seg>
<seg id=5> Parents demand higher academic records and often compare their children with other kids. They demand their children to do even better, which causes great pressure. But persuasion and communication behind the pressure are the thermometer that measures the relationship between kids and parents. </seg>
<seg id=6> If the parents beat and abuse their children, or blame them by giving a black look simply because they don't live up to their expectation, or if they make children feel they are disappointing, this undoubtedly drives the kids to a helpless situation. </seg>
<seg id=7> It is said that many adolescents who need psychiatric help are perplexed simply because the extraordinarily high expectation of their parents has put them into an inescapable corner. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The success and fast development of Singapore make parents feel that their children have far better material conditions and inevitably they think that their kids should excel them in performance. </seg>
<seg id=9> Normally, parents forget the fact that they might not be very excellent in everything when they were kids. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040308.002" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Once one and a half years old, most of the kids are sent to boarding nurseries of departments and institutions and the authorities charge a little token money. Kids come back home only once a week or even once a month. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=2> Today Singapore faces the social issue of dropping birth rates and aging of population. </seg>
<seg id=3> The younger generation are busy maintaining modern living standards and modern material enjoyments. They cannot afford to respond to the government call for early marriage and early birth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The author has a bold proposal to make, i.e. the government accepts newly-born babies. </seg>
<seg id=5> The citizens are only encouraged to give birth to babies. They don't have to worry about the fostering of children. </seg>
<seg id=6> On the one hand the government provides boarding nurseries, boarding kindergartens and even boarding primary schools and supplies 3-meal-a-day service. It charges the citizens a little token money which they can easily afford. </seg>
<seg id=7> This not only provides job opportunities for the unemployed but also frees the government from worrying whether or not such measures as baby awards, prolonging the maternity leave, promoting quality of housemaid, tax kickback, etc. will achieve the desired results. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040308.003" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> What Beijing needs to do is not just acting as the chief guide of the 6-party talk but to set its eye on China's long-term interest on the Korean Peninsula. It should take precautions and start its strategic deployments as soon as possible. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=2> To be specific, Beijing should on the one hand urge North Korea to give up its nuclear arms and one the other hand, guide North Korea onto the track of modern civilization through the transformation of Kim Jong-il regime, remove the danger of a nuclear warm from northeast Asia and keep the status quo on the Korean Peninsula so as to obtain bargaining counters in its strategic dealing with the USA. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Pyongyang, fierce of mien but faint of heart, is eager in its heart to develop its economy and merge into the international community. </seg>
<seg id=4> But this strong desire displays itself in the outer form of valiance, irrationality and sometimes not in conformity with international regulations. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> In fact, Beijing has, for a period of time, used its influence and the means of economic aid to compel Pyongyang to change its position running counter international rules. </seg>
<seg id=6> But this act still needs overall planning. </seg>
<seg id=7> The aid of Beijing to Pyongyang should not be confined to the economic level and should be extended to other social fields. It should not be limited to forcing Pyongyang to give up its nuclear program. It should focus on guiding the regime onto the road to modern civilization. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040308.004" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> In the early days when Kerry entered the arena, nobody cherished much hope on him. At that time all the focus was on the former Vermont governor Dean. </seg>
<seg id=2> But in January before the Party meeting was held in Iowa, Kerry, a dark horse, appeared and won the Party meeting and primary elections in the 2 most essential states of Iowa and New Hampshire. </seg>
<seg id=3> In the following states primary elections Kerry, on the whole, did not lose except for those states which had their own candidates </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Only in 6 week's time Kerry became the final candidate from a candidate with little prospects. All his competitive opponents were defeated one after another including Gephardt, Lieberman, Clark, Dean and Edwards. People cannot but look at Kerry's political charm with new eyes. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> In his 19 years of career as a congressman Kerry has always supported abortion and policies of environmental protection and opposed the tax reduction plan benefiting the rich. He has devoted himself to promoting the minimum wages and wishes to solve the problem of global warming. </seg>
<seg id=6> His working experience in Washington demonstrates his courage that he likes to meet the difficult social issues head on and is brave to challenge authorities. He seeks value and is never afraid of offending the minority. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040309.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> China's reform and opening-up policy started from agriculture and rural residents were the first beneficiaries of the policy. </seg>
<seg id=2> But after 1990s the substantial bias of the economic policies to big cities resulted in the basic standstill of the agrarian reform. The gap between the rural and urban regions was increasingly widened as a result. </seg>
<seg id=3> As time went on, in China appear two entirely different worlds: one is the highly prosperous cities and the other is the poor and backward countryside. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> To quote Chinese officials, the widening gap between the rich cities and the poor countryside is "a problem in the course of development" and it can be solved by sustaining the development. </seg>
<seg id=5> In other words China's coastal regions and cities should keep developing and should not be held back by the rural problems. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> However, on seeing small changes in one year and big changes in 3 years in large cities, people cannot help asking why few changes have taken place for decades in some poverty-stricken areas. </seg>
<seg id=7> Of course we have to admit the fact that the rural areas and cities differ in their developing ways, but the problem is, while investing large sums of money in urban construction and in encouraging and backing the rich middle class, whether or not the rural people occupying 70% of the whole population have enjoyed the same care and attention. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In theory it cannot claim that all the previous Chinese governments have failed to attach importance to agriculture, rural areas and peasants. </seg>
<seg id=9> But in the past years things have been more and more difficult and have become worse in the countryside. This shows that the attention paid to the countryside is becoming more and more insufficient. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040309.002" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> In any country public security departments, procuratorial organs and courts are symbols of justice and fairness and are the most important system in safeguarding social stability. </seg>
<seg id=2> But unfortunately public security departments, procuratorial organs and courts are symbols of corruption in China. </seg>
<seg id=3> According to a report released recently by the National Audit Office which last year has carried out auditing of the financial expenditures of public security departments in 26 provinces and cities, the irregular amount of money had come up to 16.5 billion RMB. </seg>
<seg id=4> The trust crisis in public security departments, procuratorial organs and courts has been known to all. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The Liu Yong event, Sun Zhigang event and the recent "BMW" incident in Heilongjiang reflect this profound distrust. </seg>
<seg id=6> The "BMW" incident is an example in point. </seg>
<seg id=7> People give much more attention and concern to this issue than to the SARS in the period of its spreading. </seg>
<seg id=8> In fact what people's attention focus on is no longer the "BMW" incident itself, but expresses the distrust on the whole law-enforcing system. </seg>
<seg id=9> Departments concerned are very clear about this, so before long they took suffocating measures against mass media. </seg>
<seg id=10> Nevertheless, problems remain there. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040309.003" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> The second round of 6-party talks on the Korean Peninsula issue has come to a conclusion as people generally expected. </seg>
<seg id=2> During the talks the parties concerned have had contacts and explorations on the exterior issues around the peninsula nuclear crisis and have reached a consensus on holding the 3rd round of talks before the end of June and on setting up a working group. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> But on such substantial issues as how North Korea should give up its nuclear weapon development program, how US should guarantee the North Korea's political and military safety after it gives up the nuclear plan and the energy supply to North Korea, etc., not only no progress has been made but also people are made to feel as if "the fast knot" is getting increasingly tight. </seg>
<seg id=4> The two leading roles  North Korea and US have demonstrated no concessions and their bottom lines remain unyielding. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> However, the fascinating thing is that US showed during the talks an attitude of not being eager to settle the problem. It gives people the impression of "procrastination ". </seg>
<seg id=6> The tactics demonstrated by US is closely associated with the present developments of the international situation and the interest it is seeking in the new developments. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040309.004" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> Never have so many bosses been imprisoned in US since Roosevelt became the president. </seg>
<seg id=2> Is it a coincidence, or have the public and investors been driven beyond forbearance in the past 3 years to the corporate crimes and other illegal acts of corporations, which resulted in the exposure of so many crimes in such a short period recently? </seg>
<seg id=3> The answer may not be simple, but it is a fact that the crimes of so many companies have been laid bare. </seg>
<seg id=4> This is a good sign for economic recovery and the restoration of investors' confidence. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> Late 1990s may be one of the most disorderly and most unfathomable periods in the history of American commerce. The sooner its influence disappears, the better. </seg>
<seg id=6> When everything settles down, the names of some companies will fade out in history. And in the end, only in the textbooks of business schools' can they be found. </seg>
<seg id=7> Some other companies such as Tyco and MCI will regroup themselves under the leadership of new teams and try to greet the coming of a new round of economic growth. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> When will the new round of economic growth come about? </seg>
<seg id=9> You, as a CEO, may have no answer. </seg>
<seg id=10> It does not matter, because the Chairman of US Federal Reserve Greenspan does not know the answer either. </seg>
</p>
</DOC>
<DOC docid="ZBN20040310.001" sysid="che">
<p>
<seg id=1> The Bush Administration intends to stimulate economy with Keynesianism, increasing expenditure (especially expenditure for national defense) on the one hand and reducing tax on the other hand. </seg>
<seg id=2> In international affairs the Bush Administration continues its free trade policy, but the trade deficit has amounted to 549 billion USD, a new high in record. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> After tax has been greatly reduced, investment and consumption do not show obvious sign of growth. </seg>
<seg id=4> The new Keynesian school represented by the celebrated British economist Wyme Godley holds that the US economy has been caught in a difficult situation and Bush's financial and economic strategy can not turn the tide. </seg>
<seg id=5> They think the so-called "market rule assuming command" is but an illusion and will naturally lead to benefiting the minority and harming the majority. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> People used to believe that in the entire world the so-called benefited minority are all in the USA and the harmed majority are all in developing countries. </seg>
<seg id=7> But now it is no longer so. </seg>
<seg id=8> Many people in American economic circles hold that today winners of globalization obviously include India and China, in addition to the US-based multi-national corporations. </seg>
<seg id=9> India occupies the domain of service economy and China takes up the manufacture realm. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> People concentrate their attention on the phenomenon that large amount of the US funds and equipments are flowing to China. But they do not see the advantage of China's high level and low income labor market. </seg>
</p>
